column7:
I'd disagree. Public image is a huge part of business. If the company does something to attract negative attention, it can cause a boycott of products. Competitors may capitalize on this to steal business. That decreases profits, which in turn decreases share price (probably). If shareholders are impacted enough, they may try to vote the leadership out of the company. Not to say it always happens this way, but look at Papa John. He got booted for being a jerk. It doesn't always happen, but it can. 

&amp;#x200B;

Having worked in public and private companies, the major difference I saw was regulation. Public companies are scrutinized for the tiniest details. Audits are a lot more painful. Work quality has to be better. There's just less room for error with regulators. So I guess for me it wasn't money-hungry capitalism that drove me out of public, but stress. And I wouldn't say the blame for the stress is on the company, but on the government who enacts the standards. Working for a public company can be downright miserable depending on your role (I was accounting). Private life is a lot better in terms of time, money, stress, etc.
